            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Meiko Kaur Ito is a product of the Bay Area's cultural confluence. Born in Daly City to a second-generation Japanese American father and a Punjabi immigrant mother, her childhood home was a vibrant fusion of traditions. The scent of her father's dashi often mingled with the aroma of her mother\u2019s roasting spices, creating a unique culinary language that would later define her career. Food was how her family communicated love, and Meiko became a fluent and passionate speaker.\n\nHer path wasn't linear. After high school, she enrolled in Hospitality Management at City College of San Francisco, but found the classroom less compelling than the real world. A turning point came when she was offered an assistant manager position with a prestigious catering company that serviced the city's art galleries. Seeing a chance to learn by doing, she left her studies, a decision she has never regretted. With relentless drive and an innate talent for event logistics and menu design, Meiko worked her way up. Today, she is the Catering Director for a major museum, orchestrating everything from intimate donor dinners to grand opening galas.\n\nNow 48, Meiko lives a life of disciplined creativity. Her workday is a storm of coordination, but her personal life is a quiet haven. She resides in a cozy one-bedroom apartment in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood she loves for its proximity to Golden Gate Park and the authentic eateries on Clement Street. Her 3.8-mile commute on the N-Judah is a cherished ritual, a time to people-watch and mentally prepare for the day. Though she enjoys a wide circle of industry acquaintances, her core social group is a small, tight-knit collection of friends\u2014an artist, a chef, and a bookseller\u2014with whom she shares dim sum on Sundays.\n\nMeiko's dream is to distill her experience into her own venture: a bespoke catering firm specializing in culturally-infused culinary events. She envisions \"Ito-Kaur Cuisine,\" a tribute to her parents and a final, creative expression of her identity. San Francisco is not just her home; it's the only place she feels her unique story could have unfolded, and the only place she can imagine writing its next chapter."
